    <item>
      <title>Jill Smokler, Who Blogged as Scary Mommy, Dies at 48</title>
      <link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/parenting/jill-smokler-dead.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/parenting/jill-smokler-dead.html</guid>
      <atom:link href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/parenting/jill-smokler-dead.html" rel="standout"></atom:link>
      <description>A mother of three, she turned a whim into an online powerhouse, sharing a warts-and-all look at parenting that attracted millions of readers.</description>
      <dc:creator>Alex Williams</dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Wed, 24 Jun 2026 04:14:43 +0000</pubDate>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Parenting</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Deaths (Obituaries)</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Blogs and Blogging (Internet)</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Children and Childhood</category>
      <media:content height="1180" medium="image" url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/23/multimedia/23Smokler--ckvb/23Smokler--ckvb-mediumSquareAt3X.jpg" width="1180"></media:content>
      <media:credit>Tribune Content Agency LLC, via Shutterstock</media:credit>
      <media:description>With the Scary Mommy blog, Jill Smokler gave parents the space to acknowledge that raising children, while deeply satisfying, was also grindingly difficult.</media:description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Lorcan O’Herlihy, Architect of Innovative Urban Housing, Dies at 66</title>
      <link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/arts/design/lorcan-oherlihy-dead.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/arts/design/lorcan-oherlihy-dead.html</guid>
      <atom:link href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/arts/design/lorcan-oherlihy-dead.html" rel="standout"></atom:link>
      <description>Arguing that architecture is a “social act,” he built affordable homes on small lots in Los Angeles and elsewhere, with an eye toward smarter, more equitable design.</description>
      <dc:creator>Clay Risen</dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2026 18:23:29 +0000</pubDate>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Architecture</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Deaths (Obituaries)</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_per">O&#39;Herlihy, Lorcan</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">California</category>
      <media:content height="1496" medium="image" url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/23/multimedia/23Oherlihy-SUBB-bzfp/23Oherlihy-SUBB-bzfp-mediumSquareAt3X.jpg" width="1497"></media:content>
      <media:credit>Michael Weschler for The New York Times</media:credit>
      <media:description>Lorcan O’Herlihy in 2000. “As global cities become denser and the need for housing greater, it is more critical than ever to design spaces that promote equity, human interaction and cultural evolution,” he said.</media:description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Charles Hinman, Who Brought New Dimensions to Painting, Dies at 93</title>
      <link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/arts/design/charles-hinman-dead.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/arts/design/charles-hinman-dead.html</guid>
      <atom:link href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/arts/design/charles-hinman-dead.html" rel="standout"></atom:link>
      <description>Starting in the early 1960s, the New York artist blurred the line between painting and sculpture with his shaped, protruding canvases.</description>
      <dc:creator>Alex Williams</dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2026 14:15:12 +0000</pubDate>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_per">Hinman, Charles</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Deaths (Obituaries)</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Art</category>
      <media:content height="1800" medium="image" url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/15/multimedia/22Hinnman-lcwf/22Hinnman-lcwf-mediumSquareAt3X.jpg" width="1800"></media:content>
      <media:credit>Jack Mitchell/Getty Images</media:credit>
      <media:description>Mr. Hinman in front of his works in 1967. Unlike the standard flat rectangular painting, some of his featured undulating curves; others, contours like cut gems.</media:description>
    </item>
